{
  "guid": "spsq",
  "name": "Step Sequencer",
  "description": "A simple note sequencer based on the sequencers in the Expert Sleepers FH-2 module. It can output CVs and/or MIDI with each of its 16 steps featuring pitch, velocity, modulation, and division settings (repeat or ratchet counts). Each substep (repeat or ratchet) can be toggled on/off via the Pattern parameter, while ties are controlled by the Ties parameter. A tie sustains a note until just after the next step begins, creating legato playback for MIDI or gliding gates with pitch CVs when tied. The sequencer supports randomization of pitches, rhythm, or both and includes internal storage for 32 sequences, usable as snapshots or patterns to build songs. Every parameter is mappable, allowing modulation via LFOs or other sources. For scale/key constraints, pair this with a Quantizer.",
  "categories": [
    "sequencing",
    "randomization",
    "MIDI",
    "clocking",
    "CV processing"
  ],
  "use_cases": [
    "Generating rhythmic and melodic patterns for modular synthesizers",
    "Creating evolving sequences via LFO modulation of step parameters",
    "Building songs by switching between stored sequences (manually or under CV control)",
    "Legato note playback in MIDI setups",
    "Gliding pitch CVs with tied notes",
    "Randomizing pitches, rhythms, or both for experimental music production"
  ],
  "gui_description": "The GUI displays an overview of the 16-step sequencer. Pitches are shown across the top, with the current step highlighted and start/end steps marked by solid bars. Edited parameters are visually emphasized, while divisions (repeats/ratchets), patterns, and ties appear graphically as stacks of blocks or longer bars. Pitch, velocity, and modulation values are displayed via thin lines to the left when applicable.",
